'''Equality of autonomy''' is a [[political philosophy]] concept of [[Amartya Sen]] that argues "that the ability and means to choose our life course should be spread as equally as possible across society"—i.e., an equal chance at [[autonomy]] or [[empowerment]].<ref name=twsO23>{{cite news |author= Sunder Katwala |title= It's equality of life chances, not literal equality, that the left espouses |work= [[The Guardian]] |date= 21 October 2010 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/oct/21/equality-life-chances-not-literal-left |accessdate= 2011-07-15}}</ref> Equality of autonomy strives to spread empowerment widely so that "given their circumstances", people have more "choice and control".<ref name=twsO24>{{cite news|title=Equality Impact Assessments |publisher=''Hull Teaching Primary Care'' |date=2011-07-15 |url=http://www.hullpct.nhs.uk/impact_assessments/ |accessdate=2011-07-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307214013/http://www.hullpct.nhs.uk/impact_assessments/ |archivedate=2012-03-07 |df= }}</ref> The concept has a slightly different emphasis from related notions, such as the value of [[Inequality in the workplace|equality in the workplace]] ("[[equal opportunity]]") or equal material wealth ("[[equality of outcome]]").
According to [[Todd May]], Sen's approach requires "[[Economic interventionism|active intervention]] of institutions like the state into people's lives" but with an aim towards "fostering of people's self-creation rather than their living conditions".<ref name=twsO25>{{cite book |author= [[Todd May]] |title= The Political Thought of Jacques Rancière: Creating Equality |publisher= The Pennsylvania State University Press |quote= Amartya Sen has developed a theory of [[distributive justice]] that, like [[John Rawls|Rawls]]', requires the active intervention of institutions like the state into people's lives, but like [[Robert Nozick|Nozick]]'s, aims that intervention at the fostering of people's self-creation rather than their living conditions. For Sen, the proper focus of a theory of justice is on what he calls ''capabilities'', and he defines those capabilities on the basis of what he calls ''functionings''. |page=20 |year= 2008 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=JJYjY8sG85kC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=%22equality+of+autonomy%22&source=bl&ots=zHHGkwrGBm&sig=J6qBAQ5E5UjlZZz4Usv0UQ_5ElI&hl=en&ei=ZpAjTrjdCpO40AH_g8ilAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22equality%20of%20autonomy%22&f=false |accessdate= 2011-07-15}}</ref> Sen argued that "the ability to convert incomes into opportunities is affected by a multiplicity of individual and social differences that mean some people will need more than others to achieve the same range of [[Capability approach|capabilities]]".<ref name=twsO45>{{cite journal |author= Anne Phillips |title= Defending Equality of Outcome |journal= Journal of Political Philosophy |year= 2004 |pages= 1–19 |url= http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/533/ |accessdate= 2011-07-15}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Capability approach]] * ''[[Development as Freedom]]'' * [[Egalitarianism]] * [[Equality of opportunity]] * [[Equality of outcome]] * [[Inequity aversion]]
