'''Trinidad María Enríquez''' (5 June 1846-20 April 1891) was a [[Peruvians|Peruvian]] teacher and student. After completing the only education available to her, she founded a school to teach other girls and complete the necessary requirements to enter university. Appealing to the president, she was granted the right to attend if an examination proved she was adequately prepared. Passing her review, 
Enríquez completed courses at the [[National University of Saint Anthony the Abbot in Cuzco]], becoming the first Peruvian woman to earn a university degree in 1878. Though she graduated, she was denied a license to practice law and fought her case through the legislature and court systems until her death in 1891.

==Early life==
Trinidad María Josefa Enríquez Ladrón de Guevara was born on 5 June 1846 in [[Cusco]], Peru to Cecilia Ladrón de Guevara y Castilla and Marcelino Enríquez. Her parents were well to do{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}}{{sfn|Vilchez Izquierdo|2006}} and on her mother's side of the family, she descended from [[Túpac Amaru]] and his son [[Túpac Amaru II]], per historian Horacio Villanueva Urteaga.{{sfn|Letona|2012}}{{sfn|Tamariz Lúcar|2016}} She enrolled at ''El Colegio de señoritas "Educandas"'' (The Educandas Preparatory School for Girls) and excelled at her studies.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} At the time, there were no higher education opportunities for women and there were no schools offering a complete high school education for the final two years of study.{{sfn|Letona|2012}}{{sfn|Tamariz Lúcar|2016}} Custom decreed that women were destined to become wives and mothers. The only training offered was restricted to upper class women and focused on preparing them with light reading, sewing and music to take their place in society.{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=107}}

==Career==
By the age of eleven, Enríquez was teaching geography courses at Educandas. She founded a women's school, known as the ''Colegio Superior para Mujeres'' (High School for Women), on 1 June 1870. Included in her curricula were courses to prepare her to take the university entrance examinations, like analytical reading, arithmetic, Castilian grammar and lexicography, hygiene, and universal history, among others.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} Enríquez based the courses she offered on the requirements needed to attain entrance to university.{{sfn|Tamariz Lúcar|2016}} Society was divided upon whether such education was necessary for women and after three years, she was forced to close the school.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} 

Wanting to pursue higher education and become a lawyer, Enríquez applied for the university, after obtaining a governmental decree allowing her to take the entrance examinations. The decree, issued on 3 October 1874 required that her independent study for two years at her own school be validated, and if found acceptable, authorized her to enter any national university.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}}{{sfn|Tamariz Lúcar|2016}} From 20 to 29 April 1875, she was examined by a jury to determine her preparedness.{{sfn|Letona|2012}} The evaluations were published and much commented upon in the regional newspapers, but Enríquez was given high marks in the tests and allowed to enter university.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} She enrolled in the [[National University of Saint Anthony the Abbot in Cuzco]]{{sfn|Vilchez Izquierdo|2006}}{{sfn|LaGreca|2009|p=91}} and graduated in 1878 with a bachelor's degree in [[jurisprudence]], as the first woman university graduate in the country.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}}{{sfn|Letona|2012}}

Forbidden by law to receive a license as an attorney, Enríquez appealed to the [[Congress of the Republic of Peru|Peruvian Congress]] and the [[Judiciary of Peru|Judiciary]]. Though [[Mariano Felipe Paz Soldán]], the [[Ministry of Justice and Human Rights (Peru)|Minister of Justice and Instruction]] was in favor of allowing women to enter the profession, others were not.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} The advent of the [[War of the Pacific]] in 1879, prevented the legislature from considering her request.{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=106}} On 5 October 1881, President [[Nicolás de Piérola]] issued a presidential authorization to allow Enríquez admission to the bar. She rejected the exception, on the basis that the law should allow any woman equal access to become a lawyer.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} After the war ended, the legislature took up Enríquez request again and after consulting with the [[Superior Courts of Justice of Peru|Superior Courts of Justice in Lima]] denied her request in 1886.{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=106}}

In 1870, Enríquez had founded the Artisan Society of Cusco, which operated a night school for workers, teaching them to read and write and educating them about their rights under the law. She also founded and edited the journal ''La voz del Cusco'' (The Voice of Cusco), which was focused on issues effecting women and wokers.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}}{{sfn|Tamariz Lúcar|2016}} The final decision of the courts on Lima was issued in 1891, by prosecutor Ricardo Espinoza, who denied the license on the basis that women lacked the physical strength and mental capacity to serve as professionals and that by granting them the rights to do so, they would become masculine.{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=110}}

==Death and legacy==
Enríquez died on 20 April 1891 in Lima, from [[brain fever]] and was buried at the [[Cementerio de la Almudena]] in Cusco.{{sfn|Vargas Sifuentes|2017}} Enríquez persistence to enter university inspired other women and by 1908 a dozen other women had been allowed to enter university;{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=112}} however, the law faculty did not enroll another woman until 1913, when Rosa Pérez Liendo was allowed to begin her studies.{{sfn|Valladares Chamorro|2012|p=113}} In 1914, her portrait was hung in the main hall of the National University of Saint Anthony the Abbot.{{sfn|Vilchez Izquierdo|2006}} In 2005, Tania Gutiérrez Samanez published a biography ''Trinidad María Enríquez'' detailing her life{{sfn|Letona|2012}} and ''Trinidad María Enríquez, una abogada en los Andes'' (Trinidad María Enríquez, an attorney in the Andes) was published by Carlos Ramos Núñez and Martín Baigorria Castillo.{{sfn|Vilchez Izquierdo|2006}}

